The problem I've always had with zeronet is that everyone has to host everything
It's so inefficient and it makes it impossible to grow past a certain point
Sites like reddit or imgur use ridiculous amounts of storage so you can't have anything like that because nobody has the space for it

My crazy idea is to split websites into tiny pieces and then spread the pieces across the network. You have to contact to other people to get all the pieces so you can view the site but you don't have to store the entire site so it can be any size. The better the network for a site, the more it can be broken up because the network can be relied on to have all the pieces at all times.
I don't know if it's actually feasible but that's my solution to the problem of storage.
But you wouldn't need to download the whole site, only the pieces you need at the moment e.g. the page you are visiting but not that page from 3 years ago that you aren't interested in
I'm making a useful infographic to explain my proposed method that I just made up but inevitably probably has been tried by somebody before
First: https://i.sli.mg/Vw74CZ.png
Second: https://i.sli.mg/RWYrBw.png
there's probably some massive flaw that I'm not noticing but so far it's smooth sailing
You still have to host the optional files forever though and there's no guarantee they will be hosted
The hard part is designating and distributing pieces to make sure the site is always available

One potential solution I've come up with is hosting is dynamic, each host automatically stores and discards pieces depending on their availability in the network. If a piece becomes rare then users will begin hosting it until it becomes common again. At first everyone will have to host every piece because there won't be overlapping users, but once you get a few hundred users on average for every hour of the day then people will only be hosting a couple of pieces rather than the whole site. As sites with user created content become more popular they become bigger, but that means there are more hosts so the storage requirements don't expand very much.
